Hi
TV-Head electronics project originally inspired by Vivian's TV head, but taken further by the addition of a few interesting modules and, of course, entirely coded by myself.

This project serves three purposes. Firstly, and the more "societaly important" one is for my academic success. I am using this project as my end-of-program research topic for my TIM DEC. Secondly, the "fun" reason, is for my cosplays. Not only am I learning a ton by messing around with different electronics, but I'm having a blast by making things even as simple as an OV2640 camera work. It'll help me greatly expand my list of skills and add a string to my bow when it comes to cosplaying techniques. Bonus point for making me one of the only (or at least as far as I've seen) cosplayer originating from Québec to use electronics with such a degree of complexity, and I am happy to share my progress on GitHub for all aspiring cosplayers to learn from (WE NEED MORE WORKING TV HEADS IN CONVENTIONS!!). The third purpose is, of course, to share my progress as I have just said. I'd love to see more electronics being used in conventions, or at least more than simple LEDs animations, but I understand that it is not something easy to do. You need to learn a lot of different skills from coding to soldering, and those take time, money, and effort just to be able to do something usable.

The fourth secret purpose is to be able to eventually do the electronics parts of my partner's cosplays... might as well make those newly acquired skills useful to others, no?

Everything is coded in half-english, half-french. Why? Tokébakicitte! I'm from Québec, and speak & write both in English and French. That includes my code.

Oh, and side-note, I probably won't commit every little change to this repository. It might be irregularly scheduled big steps composed of a lot of different things. Since I started this project before actually having to do reports (for school), I'm commiting when I think about it, and that might not be as often as it could. I'll try to keep the code as commented as possible & the commit messages as useful as possible.

-- 

I made it work with Voice Recognition
Issue: Seems like PlatformIO doesnt auto-generate srmodels (.pio/build/esp32-s3-devkitc1-n16r8) so I have to do it everytime you clean and build (after building, before flashing) (after remaking the build folder)

Answer: 
AT THIS LEVEL
PS C:\Users\mimil\OneDrive\Documents\PlatformIO\Projects\TV_Head_v1> (!! Root of your project !!)
RUN THIS
python "C:\Users\mimil\OneDrive\Documents\PlatformIO\Projects\TV_Head_v1\components\esp-sr\model\movemodel.py" `
    -d1 "C:\Users\mimil\OneDrive\Documents\PlatformIO\Projects\TV_Head_v1\sdkconfig.esp32-s3-devkitc1-n16r8" `
    -d2 "C:\Users\mimil\OneDrive\Documents\PlatformIO\Projects\TV_Head_v1\components\esp-sr" `
    -d3 "C:\Users\mimil\OneDrive\Documents\PlatformIO\Projects\TV_Head_v1\.pio\build\esp32-s3-devkitc1-n16r8"

It'll make them from movemodel.py ("d0"), referencing your sdkconfig (d1), using your esp-sr component (d2), and write them (srmodel folder with your language models) in the good folder (d3)

So basically: 
1- Do your update
2- Clean
3- Build
4- Do the python command above
5- Flash to board
6- Serial monitor (and reset board to make it start with the new code obviously)

To add voice commands: (dans le root folder, donc TV_Head_vXXX)
py -3 "C:\Users\mimil\OneDrive\Documents\PlatformIO\Projects\TV_Head_v1\components\esp-sr\tool\multinet_g2p.py" -t "Cheese;Cake;Christmas Tree, Tree; Christmas Gift, Gift; Flashbang, Think Fast Chucklenuts; Flashlight, Let there be light;Brightness normal; Brightness down; Brightness up; Brightness minimum; Brightness maximum;"
Basically on utilise l'outil g2p de multinet pour lui faire generer du phonetique qu'on met dans le sdk/menuconfig
l'exemple en haut return:
in: Cheese;Cake;Christmas Tree, Tree; Christmas Gift, Gift; Flashbang, Think Fast Chucklenuts; Flashlight, Let there be light;Brightness normal; Brightness down; Brightness up; Brightness minimum; Brightness maximum;
out: pmZ;KdK;KRgSMcS TRm,TRm;KRgSMcS GgFT,GgFT;FLasBal,vglK FaST KcKLcNcTS;FLasLiT,LfT jfR Bm LiT;BRiTNcS NeRMcL;BRiTNcS DtN;BRiTNcS cP;BRiTNcS MgNcMcM;BRiTNcS MaKScMcM;;

Note to self: If python is wrong again (3.14 instead of 3.13 for example) reinstall, update PATH, and then check the platformio.exe --version to see if Core needs to be re-installed to fit python

To upload data folder: 
pio run --target buildfs
pio run --target uploadfs